#: index.docbook:78
msgid "What is &kblackbox;?"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:80
msgid ""
"&kblackbox; is a superb :-) graphical logical game, inspired by the "
"<application>emacs</application> blackbox. Major part of this help file is "
"based on the original <application>emacs</application>'s help."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:85
msgid ""
"&kblackbox; is a game of hide and seek played on an grid of boxes. Your "
"opponent (the Random number generator, in this case) has hidden several "
"balls within this box. By shooting rays into the box and observing where "
"they emerge it is possible to deduce the positions of the hidden balls. The "
"fewer rays you use to find the balls, the better (the lower) your score."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:95
msgid "Game description"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:97
msgid ""
"In the first part of this section a description of the game board will be "
"given. The second part deals with user interaction with the game board and "
"finally in the third part the actual game rules are explained."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:103
msgid "Game board description"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:105
msgid "The following types of fields are found on the game board:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Black squares"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "The black box. Here you must mark the squares you think a ball is in."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Green squares"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "These are the lasers, shooting rays of light when switched on."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Light Grey squares"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Nothing here of interest, this is just a border."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Blue balls"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid ""
"<quote>There must be one!</quote> you think. These mark where you suspect a "
"ball is placed in the black box."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Cyan balls"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Show where the balls actually are."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Red balls"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Incorrectly positioned balls you have marked are indicated in red."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Brown squares"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:107
msgid "Marking color"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:149
msgid ""
"The names of colors are used just for identifying the different types of the "
"fields in this text. They <emphasis>might not</emphasis> be in any relation "
"with the actual color of the fields. Simply said: the black box is in the "
"centre, around are the lasers and around them is the border. Remap the "
"colors yourself :-)."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:159
msgid "User Interaction"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:161
msgid ""
"The cursor can be moved around the box with the standard cursor movement "
"keys or the mouse. Switching of lasers or marking of black boxes is done by "
"the <mousebutton>left</mousebutton> mouse button, or by pressing "
"<keycap>Return</keycap> or <keycap>Enter</keycap> keys."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:167
msgid ""
"You can mark the fields, where a ball can't be, too. Just press the "
"<mousebutton>right</mousebutton>"
" mouse button. It often helps you to find an area, where a ball could "
"possibly be. To clear any marks (blue or brown) press the "
"<mousebutton>left</mousebutton> mouse button. Brown marks can't overwrite "
"blue marks. This way you can't erase the blue marks (guessed balls) by "
"accident when playing with the <mousebutton>right</mousebutton> mouse button."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:175
msgid ""
"When you think the configuration of balls you have placed is correct, press "
"the <mousebutton>middle</mousebutton> mouse button. You will be informed "
"whether you are correct or not, and be given your score. Your score is the "
"number of letters and numbers around the outside of the box plus five for "
"each incorrectly placed ball. If you placed any balls incorrectly, they will "
"be indicated with red fields, and their actual positions indicated with cyan "
"fields."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:186
msgid "Game rules"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:188
msgid ""
"You have to find balls hidden in the black box. Your means are limited - you "
"can just fire lasers which are around the box. There are three possible "
"outcomes for each ray you send into the box:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:193
msgid "Detour"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:193
msgid ""
"The ray is deflected and emerges somewhere other than where you sent it in. "
"On the playfield, detours are denoted by matching pairs of numbers - one "
"where the ray went in, and the other where it came out."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:193
msgid "Reflection"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:193
msgid ""
"The ray is reflected and emerges in the same place it was sent in. On the "
"playfield, reflections are denoted by the letter <guilabel>R</guilabel>."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:193
msgid "<term>Hit</term>"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:193
msgid ""
"The ray strikes a ball directly and is absorbed. It does not emerge from the "
"box. On the playfield, hits are denoted by the letter <guilabel>H</guilabel>."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:218
msgid ""
"The rules for how balls deflect rays are simple and are best shown by "
"example."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:221
msgid ""
"As a ray approaches a ball it is deflected ninety degrees. Rays can be "
"deflected multiple times. In the diagrams below, the dashes represent empty "
"box locations and the letter <guilabel>O</guilabel> represents a ball. The "
"entrance and exit points of each ray are marked with numbers as described "
"under <link linkend=\"detour\">Detour</link> above. Note that the entrance "
"and exit points are always interchangeable. <guilabel>*</guilabel> denotes "
"the path taken by the ray."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:230
msgid ""
"Note carefully the relative positions of the ball and the ninety degree "
"deflection it causes."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:233
msgid ""
"1                                            \n"
"- * - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -       \n"
"- * - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -       \n"
"1 * * - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -         - O - - - - O -       \n"
"- - O - - - - -         - - O - - - - -         - - * * * * - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - * * * * * 2     3 * * * - - * - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - * - - - -         - - - O - * - -      \n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - * - - - -         - - - - * * - -       \n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - * - - - -         - - - - * - O -       \n"
"2                         3"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:246
msgid ""
"As mentioned above, a reflection occurs when a ray emerges from the same "
"point it was sent in. This can happen in several ways:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:251
msgid ""
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - O - - -         - - O - O - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"R * * * * - - - -         - - - * - - - -          O - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - O - - -         - - - * - - - -        R - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - * - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - * - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -       R * * * * - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - O - - -          - - - - - - - -"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:261
msgid ""
"In the first example, the ray is deflected downwards by the upper ball, then "
"left by the lower ball, and finally retraces its path to its point of "
"origin. The second example is similar. The third example is a bit anomalous "
"but can be rationalized by realizing the ray never gets a chance to get into "
"the box. Alternatively, the ray can be thought of as being deflected "
"downwards and immediately emerging from the box."
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:268
msgid "A hit occurs when a ray runs straight into a ball:"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:270
msgid ""
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -          - - - - O - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - O - - -        H * * * * - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -       H * * * * O - - -          - - - * - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - O - - -          - - - O - - - -\n"
"H * * * O - - - -         - - - - - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -          - - - - - - - -\n"
"- - - - - - - -         - - - - - - - -          - - - - - - - -"
msgstr ""

#: index.docbook:280
msgid ""
"Be sure to compare the second example of a hit with the first example of a "
"reflection."
msgstr ""

